    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-02-02T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-02-02T17:00:00-05:00" n="245"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d245">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72111Y2/7</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJW1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gerard</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-02-02T17:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 2, 1917, 5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3857. Your 4929, January 26, 11 a.m., and 4973, January 31, 9 p.m.<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d245fn1">Telegram of Jan. 31 not printed.</note> You are instructed
                    to take up the matter personally with <persName corresp="#p_ZDA1"
                        >Zimmermann</persName> or <persName>Hollweg</persName> and insist upon being
                    informed immediately whether any Americans are among the prisoners brought in on
                    the <hi rend="italic">Yarrowdale:</hi>
                    <note n="2" xml:id="d245fn2">The names of the American citizens on the <hi
                            rend="italic">Yarrowdale</hi> were given to Ambassador <persName
                            corresp="#p_GJW1">Gerard</persName> by the German Foreign Office Feb. 1,
                        and the telegram containing them reached the Department Feb. 2 at 6 p.m.
                        (File No. 763.72111Y2/10).</note> Let nothing be undone to determine this
                    fact at <pb facs="0382" n="210" xml:id="pg_210"/> the earliest moment. If there
                    are Americans among the prisoners, emphatically, vigorously insist both formally
                    and in person upon their release, as there is no authority in law for the
                    imprisonment of neutrals taken on board enemy merchantmen unless the vessel
                    takes part in hostilities. See rules laid down in Hague Convention XI.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
